ix du Sud (1945-1970): génesis y contextos de la primera colección francesa de literatura latinoamericana -- t3: Epistemologies -- tWorld literature or Earth literature? Remarks on a distinction -- tThe World-Literary formation of Antonio Candido -- tOn the concept figure of the Global South, and ecological narrative promises and deceits -- tOrientalismo y realismo mágico al revés. Juan Rulfo y Salman Rushdie o los desafíos del Sur global para la literatura mundial -- tHacia una teoría de la circulación, con énfasis en la circulación de las ideas -- tTransArea Tangier: The city and the literatures of the world -- tList of contributors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aHow can we talk about World Literature if we do not actually examine the world as a whole? Research on World Literature commonly focuses on the dynamics of a western center and a southern periphery, ignoring the fact that numerous literary relationships exist beyond these established constellations of thinking and reading within the Global South. Re-Mapping World Literature suggests a different approach that aims to investigate new navigational tools that extend beyond the known poles and meridians of current literary maps. Using the example of Latin American literatures, this study provides innovative insights into the literary modeling of shared historical experiences, epistemological crosscurrents, and book market processes within the Global South which thus far have received scant attention. The contributions to this volume, from renowned scholars in the fields of World and Latin American literatures, assess travelling aesthetics and genres, processes of translation and circulation of literary works, as well as the complex epistemological entanglements and shared worldviews between Latin America, Africa and Asia. A timely book that embraces highly innovative perspectives, it will be a must-read for all scholars involved in the field of the global dimensions of literature.  afunded by European Research Council (ERC)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aCanon (Literature)vCongresses. 0aGlobalization in literaturevCongresses. 0aLatin American literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aLatin American literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aLiterature (General). 0aLiterature and globalizationvCongresses. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aPublishers and PublishingzSouthern HemispherevCongresses. 4aBuchmarkt. 4aGlobaler Süden. 4aLateinamerika /Literatur. 4aWeltliteratur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aBook markets.  aGlobal South.  aLatin American literatures.  aWorld Literature.1 aLoy, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomínguez, César, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLink, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevés, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Gesine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuerrero, Gustavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerlinghaus, Hermann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoyos, Héctor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrado, Ignacio M. Sánchez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l